etymologies: late 16th century; earliest use found in Raphael Holinshed (c1525–?1580), historian. From Middle French, French suffragant (adjective) auxiliary, subordinate, (noun) bishop considered in relation to the archbishop of his province, supporter, helper, alteration of Anglo-Norman and Old French, Middle French suffragan, suffragain after classical Latin suffrāgant-, suffrāgans, present participle of suffrāgārī

definitions: A bishop considered in relation to the metropolitan or archbishop of his province. Also: a bishop appointed to assist a diocesan bishop. Compare "suffragan", "suffragan".

Of a bishop or bishopric: subordinate to a metropolitan or archiepiscopal see and its incumbent; (without construction) designating such a bishop or bishopric. Later also: designating a bishop appointed to assist a diocesan bishop.
